constexpr auto sum_of_first_elements(const std::array<std::map<uint8_t, uint32_t>>& array) {
  auto sum = 0;
  for (const auto& map : array) {
    sum += map.begin()->second;
  }
  return sum;
}
```

This expression is constexpr because it is evaluated at compile time. This means that it can be used in places where a compile-time constant is required, such as in a template argument or a constant expression.

In C++11, `constexpr` functions are more limited compared to C++14 and later. For a function to compute a value like a sum using only a return statement, you'll typically need to use a helper structure or template recursion. However, achieving this directly in a return statement is quite tricky due to the limitations.

You can implement a constexpr function to calculate the sum using a helper struct or through template metaprogramming techniques. Here’s an example using a fixed-size approach to traverse an `std::array`:

```cpp
#include <array>
#include <map>
#include <cstdint>

constexpr uint32_t sum_first_elements(const std::array<std::map<uint8_t, uint32_t>, 3>& arr, size_t index) {
    return (index < arr.size()) ? arr[index].begin()->second + sum_first_elements(arr, index + 1) : 0;
}

constexpr uint32_t sum(const std::array<std::map<uint8_t, uint32_t>, 3>& arr) {
    return sum_first_elements(arr, 0);
}

// Example usage:
constexpr std::array<std::map<uint8_t, uint32_t>, 3> myArray = {{
    {{1, 10}},
    {{2, 20}},
    {{3, 30}}
}};

constexpr uint32_t result = sum(myArray); // result will be 60
```

This code calculates the sum of the first elements of the maps within the array at compile time, following C++11's `constexpr` limitations. Adjust the size of the `std::array` according to your needs.

